revision.text:
{{unreferenced|date=October 2010}}

'''Agenția de Presă RADOR''' is the largest press monitoring center in [[Romania]], established in 1990. RADOR editors monitor news published in Romanian language and in other 15 foreign languages: from audiovisual media – 57 radio and TV stations, from the written media – 150 newspapers and news agencies on all continents.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}

RADOR publishes news, interviews, analyses and comments grouped in specialised feeds on [[politics]], [[economy]], [[science]], as well as specialised bulletins: „România văzută din străinătate” ("Romania Seen From Abroad"), „Români de pretutindeni” ("Romanians From Everywhere"), „Revista presei internaționale” ("The International Press Summary"), „Economia mondială” ("Worldwide Economy"), „Economia românească” ("Romanian Economy"), „Cei 27 pentru Europa” ("27 for Europe"), „Balcanii și Marea Neagră” ("The [[Balkans]] and The [[Black Sea]]"), „Universul Științei” ("The Universe of Science"). RADOR also maintains a website.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}

== History ==

Agenția de presă RADOR was founded on June 16, 1921, replacing the first national news agency, disbanded in 1916 when Romania entered WWI.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}

RADOR was the only Romanian large national agency in the interwar period. During that time, "RADOR" name was derived from "Radio Orient"; nowadays, "RADOR" means "Radio Observator".{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}

Apart from its press monitoring service, RADOR also encompasses the "[[Dimitrie Gusti]]" Documentation Center (that creates daily, weekly and quarterly calendars of events) and the RADOR Library (an important documentation source for all [[Radio Romania]] departments. The library has about 55.000 volumes, including rare books and princeps editions).{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}

== External links ==
*[http://www.rador.ro/ RADOR's official site]

