{{Politics of Burundi}}
'''Parliamentary elections''' were held in [[Burundi]] on 4 July 2005. The result was a victory for the [[National Council for the Defense of Democracy – Forces for the Defense of Democracy]] (CNDD–FDD), which won 64 of the 118 seats in the [[National Assembly (Burundi)|National Assembly]]
==Conduct== Voting was largely peaceful throughout the country during election day. Observers deemed the polls generally free, fair, and transparent. Major political parties accepted the results as legitimate.
==Results== ===National Assembly=== In order to ensure the 60%-40% ethnic split and 30% quota for women, a further 18 members, including the three Twa representatives foreseen by the Electoral Code, were co-opted after the elections.
{| class=wikitable style=text-align:right !rowspan=2|Party !rowspan=2|Votes !rowspan=2|% !colspan=3|Seats |- !Elected !Co-opted !Total |- |- |align=left|[[National Council for the Defense of Democracy – Forces for the Defense of Democracy|CNDD–FDD]]||1,417,800||58.55||59||5||64 |- |align=left|[[Front for Democracy in Burundi]]||525,336||21.70||25||5||30 |- |align=left|[[Union for National Progress]]||174,575||7.21||10||5||15 |- |align=left|[[National Council for the Defense of Democracy]]||100,366||4.14||4||0||4 |- |align=left|[[Movement for the Rehabilitation of Citizens – Rurenzangemero]]||51,730||2.14||2||0||2 |- |align=left|[[Party for National Recovery]]||42,223||1.74||0||0||0 |- |align=left|Other parties and independents||109,396||4.51||0||0||0 |- |align=left|Reserved seats for [[Twa]]s||–||–||–||3||3 |- |align=left|Invalid/blank votes||24,575||–||–||–||– |- |align=left|'''Total'''||'''2,446,001'''||'''100'''||'''100'''||'''18'''||'''118''' |- |align=left|Registered voters/turnout||3,167,124||77.23||–||–||– |- |align=left colspan=7|Source: [http://africanelections.tripod.com/bi.html#2005_National_Assembly_Election African Elections Database] |}
===Senate=== Following the National Assembly elections, the Senate was indirectly elected on 29 July. Of the 49 Senate members, 34 were elected by electoral colleges formed by councillors, three were co-opted [[Twa]]s, four were former Presidents, and eight further members were co-opted to ensure that at least 30% of its members were women.<ref>[http://africanelections.tripod.com/indirect.html Indirect Legislative Elections in Sub-Saharan Africa] African Elections Database</ref> A total of 119 candidates stood for election to the Senate.<ref>[http://www.ipu.org/parline-e/reports/arc/2368_05.htm Burundi Sénat (Senate): Elections held in 2005] IPU</ref>
