The '''Lele''' (or '''Leele'''), also known as '''Bashilele''' or '''Usilele''', are a subgroup of the [[Kuba Kingdom|Kuba people]] in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]].<ref>''Encyclopedia of African Peoples'' (Fitzroy Dearborn Publishers, Chicago and London, 2000), s.v. Lele (p. 125).</ref> They traditionally live in the [[Kasai River]] region,<ref>[[Mary Douglas]], ''[[The Lele of the Kasai]]'' (1963), ch. 1.</ref> but since the 1950s many have migrated to [[Kinshasa]].<ref>[[Mary Douglas]], "Sorcery Accusations Unleashed: The Lele Revisited", in ''[[Implicit Meanings]]'' (2nd ed., [[Routledge]], 1999), pp. 78-80.</ref> There are currently about 30,000 Lele, of which 26,000 speak the [[Lele language (Democratic Republic of the Congo)|Lele language]].<ref>{{Ethnologue16|lel|Lele language}}</ref>

