{{Politics of Comoros}}

The '''Movement for Democracy and Progress''' ({{lang-fr|Mouvement pour la Démocratie et le Progrès}}, MDP), also known as the '''People's Democratic Movement''' (''Mouvement Démocratique Populaire'') was a political party in the [[Comoros]].

==History==
Based in [[Moroni, Comoros|Moroni]],<ref>Tom Lansford (2015) ''Political Handbook of the World 2015'', CQ Press</ref> the party campaigned for the constitution approved in a [[Comorian constitutional referendum, 1992|1992 referendum]], and contested the [[Comorian legislative election, 1992|subsequent parliamentary elections]] later in the year. Although the party received the highest vote share at 10.4%, it won only three seats in the [[Assembly of the Union of the Comoros|Assembly of the Union]], whilst the [[Union of Democrats for Development]] won seven seats.<ref>[http://africanelections.tripod.com/km.html#1992_Federal_Assembly_Election Elections in the Comoros] African Elections Database</ref>

In the [[Comorian legislative election, 1993|early parliamentary elections]] the following year the party won only two seats. In 1994 the MDP joined with other opposition to form the Forum for National Recovery (FRN), an alliance opposed to President [[Said Mohamed Djohar]].

The MDP nominated [[Abbas Djoussouf]] as its candidate for the [[Comorian presidential election, 1996|1996 presidential elections]]. Djoussouf finished second in the first round of voting, progressing to the runoff, where he was defeated by UDD candidate [[Mohamed Taki Abdoulkarim]] by a margin of 64%–36%. The MDP subsequently boycotted the [[Comorian legislative election, 1996|parliamentary elections]] later in the year. However, Djoussouf was appointed Prime Minister in November 1998. Following a [[1999 Comorian coup d'état|coup]] in 1999, the MDP left the FRN, as some member parties had supported the coup.

Djoussouf was the MDP candidate again for the [[Comorian presidential election, 2002|2002 presidential elections]], but finished fourth out of the nine candidates in the first round. Prior to the [[Comorian legislative election, 2004|2004 parliamentary elections]] the MDP joined the [[Camp of the Autonomous Islands]] alliance. The alliance won 12 of the 18 elected and all 15 of the indirectly-elected seats.

