The '''Socialist Party of Guinea''' was a [[political party]] in [[Guinea]], founded ahead of the [[French legislative election, November 1946|November 1946 National Assembly election]].<ref>''[https://books.google.com/books?id=sRONZK-0aPIC&pg=PA806 Die Wahl der Parlamente und anderer Staatsorgane Halbbd. 1]''. Berlin [u.a.]: de Gruyter, 1969. p. 806</ref> The party grew out of the [[Fulani]] Club at the [[École William Ponty]].<ref>Apter, David E., Harry Eckstein, and Gunnar Heckscher. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=xIM4AAAAIAAJ Comparative Politics: A Reader]''. New York: Free Press, 1963. p. 699</ref> The list of the Socialist Party for the election consisted of [[Mamba Sano]] (a Forestier leader) and [[Barry Diawadou]] (president of AGV). The list won one of the two seats accorded to Guinea, and Sano was elected.<ref>Morgenthau, Ruth Schachter. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=43kKAQAAIAAJ Political Parties in French-Speaking West Africa]''. Oxford studies in African affairs. Oxford: Clarendon, 1964. p. 224</ref> All in all, the list of the party had obtained 30,982 votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/histoire/biographies/IVRepublique/sano-mamba-01011900.asp|title=Formulaire de recherche dans la base de données des députés français depuis 1789 - Assemblée nationale|first=Assemblée|last=Nationale|publisher=|accessdate=12 March 2017}}</ref>

